06042nam a22008535i 9780231511957DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008020306  a97802315119577 a10.7312/beck140602doi  a(DE-B1597)458650  a(OCoLC)979574875  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV40.3b.L49 2008 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a361.309227300aLifting Our Voices :bThe Journeys Into Family Caregiving of Professional Social Workers /ced. by Joyce Beckett. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b3 illus.; 11 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Contributors -- t1. Caregiving -- t2. Once, Twice, Always a Caregiver: Career Caregiving for Parents Who Abused Alcohol -- t3. Responding to My Sister’s Addiction: Fostering Resilience in My Nieces -- t4. Caring for My Grandmother: The Birth of a Gerontological Social Worker -- t5. Not an Option but a Duty: Caring for My Mother -- t6. “My Last Born Shall Care for Me and Mine”: Caring for Siblings and Mother -- t7. Caring for My Mother: Four Phases of Caregiving -- t8. Aunt Doris’s Moves -- t9. Closing Muriel’s House: Caring for My Mother -- t10. Social Worker Husband as Caregiver of Social Worker Wife -- t11. What Goes Around Comes Around: Career Caregiving in the Caring Village -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLifting Our Voices is the only book to explore the dual roles of professional social workers who are also family caregivers and the only collection on caregiving in which the majority of contributors are African American. After discussing the relevant literature, Lifting Our Voices vividly and sensitively presents the caregiving experiences of ten professional social workers. Using professional and theoretical knowledge and skills, each contributor draws implications for various levels of social work and human service interventions. These poignant descriptions and analyses recount both the frustrations and barriers of negotiating social service agencies and other institutions and the joys and triumphs of family caregiving. Lifting Our Voices frankly discusses how a professional education either prepares or fails to equip an individual with the skills for successful intervention on behalf of a loved one. Contributors hail from rich and varied backgrounds, revealing the importance of age, ethnicity, gender, marital status, and gerontological expertise in the practice of family caregiving. These essays explore situations rarely reported on in the literature, such as caregivers and care recipients who represent the lifespan from preschool to retirement. Lifting Our Voices graphically describes types of caregiving that are seldom discussed, including simultaneous caregiving to multiple family members and reciprocal and sequential caregiving, thus broadening and refining the very concepts of "caregiving" and "family."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCaregivers - Family relationships - United States. 0aCaregiversxFamily relationshipszUnited States. 0aSocial workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSocial workerszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBeckett, Joyce O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckett, Joyce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBryant, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, King E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Joyce 